        "client_msg_id": "82DD40DC-A456-4019-8377-8A9D08F92108",
        "text": "I remember the path that the mouse has moved, take a bounding box of that path, take the center of the box, and use that as the local center of rotation. I also discard older segments of the path, keeping roughly 4pi*r of them, since that's enough to figure out roughly where the local center ought to be.\n\nThe logic for switching between modes on the fly (horizontal, vertical, or angular) is a bit dodgy. That's something that could be better, but there are also unavoidable edge cases — like when dragging rightward at the bottom of the circle (which could mean \"increase the value\" when treating the input as horizontal or \"decrease the value\" when treating it as angular), so my current approach is just to pick whichever one seems most likely and kinda lock-in on it after a handful of samples.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
